(2428, 160886, '2012-10-14 16:08:23', '"A marked differential distribution of CaBP[calbindin]-like\nimmunoreactivity was observed in the hippocampal\nformation between the dentate gyrus, CA3 and CA1\nregions (Fig. 3A). In the dentate region the molecular\nlayer of the upper and lower blade and the\ngl anule cell layer both showed relatively dense staining\nwith clear evidence of its localization within cell\nbodies. A plexus of immunoreactive fibers, arising in\ngranule cells, could be seen to converge in the hilar\nzone and course through this area to run parallel\nwith the CA3 pyramidal cell layer in the stratum radiatum. The distribution of these fibers correspond precisely with the projection of the mossy\nfiber system. No immunoreactive cells were located\nin the CA3 pyramidal cell layer (Fig. 3B) nor was\nthere any labeling of the efferent fibers of these cells\ncoursing in the fimbria and/or the Schaffer collateral\nsystem. A few intensely stained cells with widely\ndispersed processes were located in the radiatum/lacunosum\nregion of CA3. In the CA1 region, pyramidal\ncells and their apical dendrites were moderately\nstained for CaBP (Fig. 3C). Although these cells\nwere located throughout the septo-temporal axis\nthere appeared to be a slightly greater number of the\nmore temporal aspect of the CA1 region. In the\nstratum radiatum/lacunosum of CAI a thin but\ndistinct bundle of fibers could be seen coursing\nparallel to the pyramidal cell layer. In addition a few\nscattered but intensely staining cells were detected in the stratum lacunosum."', 'p 225 left', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2429, 160886, '2012-10-14 16:08:23', '"Two antibodies were used in these experiments.\nThe first (S76-4) was raised in a sheep against\npurified chick duodenal CaBP and cross-reacts with\nCaBP from numerous other tissues in this species,\nincluding the brain. The second was raised in a\nrabbit (R78-2) against purified human cerebellar\nCaBP and detects CaBP in the brain, kidney, pituitary\nand a number of other tissues with the exception\nof the gut."', 'p 223 right bot', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2430, 160886, '2012-10-14 16:08:23', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2431, 160888, '2012-10-14 16:08:23', '"In the\ncerebellum only Purkinje cells are stained, in the\nhippocampus only dentate granule cells and CA1\npyramidal neurons and in the olfactory bulb only\nperiglomerular cells contain CaBP [calbindin]."', 'p 228 left', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2432, 160888, '2012-10-14 16:08:23', '"Two antibodies were used in these experiments.\nThe first (S76-4) was raised in a sheep against\npurified chick duodenal CaBP and cross-reacts with\nCaBP from numerous other tissues in this species,\nincluding the brain. The second was raised in a\nrabbit (R78-2) against purified human cerebellar\nCaBP and detects CaBP in the brain, kidney, pituitary\nand a number of other tissues with the exception\nof the gut."', 'p 223 right bot', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2433, 160888, '2012-10-14 16:08:23', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2434, 160890, '2012-10-14 16:08:23', '"In the principal cell layers some\nparvalbumin-IR neurons showed the typical features of pyramidal basket cells. Parvalbumin-positive puncta, largely representing the axons of local neurons, surround the cell bodies and proximal dendrites of all pyramidal and granule cells."', 'p 32 left top', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2435, 160890, '2012-10-14 16:08:23', '"Adjacent sections were incubated for different antigens, first in 20% normal goat (sections for calretinin, calbindin \nD28k and parvalbumin) or normal rabbit serum (sections \nfor GABA) for 45 min, and then in rabbit anti-calretinin (49)\n(1:2000), rabbit anti-calbindin D28k (1:1000), rabbit anti-parvalbumin (1:1000) (3,6) or mouse anti-GABA (47) (1:50) for two days."', 'p 30 left mid', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2436, 160890, '2012-10-14 16:08:23', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2437, 160892, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Calbindin D28k immunoreactivity was present in\nthe superficial pyramidal cells of the CA1 area, and in the dentate granule cells and their axons."', 'p 32 left top', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2438, 160892, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Adjacent sections were incubated for different antigens, first in 20% normal goat (sections for calretinin, calbindin \nD28k and parvalbumin) or normal rabbit serum (sections \nfor GABA) for 45 min, and then in rabbit anti-calretinin (49)\n(1:2000), rabbit anti-calbindin D28k (1:1000), rabbit anti-parvalbumin (1:1000) (3,6) or mouse anti-GABA (47) (1:50) for two days."', 'p 30 left mid', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2439, 160892, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2440, 160894, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Most of the GABA-negative, calretinin-positive cells were found in the hilus of the dentate gyrus (Fig. IA-D) or in stratum lucidum of the CA3 area (Fig. 2A, B), but occasionally, GABA-negative cells occurred also in the CA1 subfield."', 'p 33 left top', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2441, 160894, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Adjacent sections were incubated for different antigens, first in 20% normal goat (sections for calretinin, calbindin \nD28k and parvalbumin) or normal rabbit serum (sections \nfor GABA) for 45 min, and then in rabbit anti-calretinin (49)\n(1:2000), rabbit anti-calbindin D28k (1:1000), rabbit anti-parvalbumin (1:1000) (3,6) or mouse anti-GABA (47) (1:50) for two days."', 'p 30 left mid', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2442, 160894, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2443, 160896, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"The analysis showed that none of the 372 calretinin-IR neurons, encountered in 12 sections, was immunoreactive for parvalbumin in any regions or layers of the hippocampus and dentate gyrus (Table 3, Fig. 4).  Similarly, no parvalbumin-IR cells (681 examined) contained calretinin."', 'p 33 right top', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2444, 160896, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Adjacent sections were incubated for different antigens, first in 20% normal goat (sections for calretinin, calbindin \nD28k and parvalbumin) or normal rabbit serum (sections \nfor GABA) for 45 min, and then in rabbit anti-calretinin (49)\n(1:2000), rabbit anti-calbindin D28k (1:1000), rabbit anti-parvalbumin (1:1000) (3,6) or mouse anti-GABA (47) (1:50) for two days."', 'p 30 left mid', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2445, 160896, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2446, 160898, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Cells in the first group [of calretinin-immunoreactive cells] were confined to stratum lucidum and had spiny dendrites (Fig. 2C, D). Their dendritic arbor was the major source of the dense network\nin stratum lucidum (Fig. 2A, B)."', 'p 5 left mid', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2447, 160898, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"The sections were incubated first in 20% normal goat serum (NGS; 45 min), then in rabbit anti-calretinin antiserum (84) (1:2000, two days).', 'p 2 right top', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2448, 160898, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2449, 160900, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', 'Calretinin-immunoreactive spiny cells and their dendrites are restricted to the hilus.', 'p 9 left bot', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2450, 160900, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"The sections were incubated first in 20% normal goat serum (NGS; 45 min), then in rabbit anti-calretinin antiserum (84) (1:2000, two days).', 'p 2 right top', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2451, 160900, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2452, 160902, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Putative neurogliaform cells expressing high level of  alpha-actinin-2\nin the soma were tested further to establish their neurochemical\nprofile. In stratum lacunosum-moleculare all cells immunopositive\nfor  alpha-actinin-2 (n = 50) coexpressed COUP-TFII and a high\nlevel of the  alpha1 subunit of the GABAA receptor in the somatodendritic\nmembrane (GABAA-alpha 1, n = 48), and the majority was also\nimmunopositive for reelin (n = 45) (Fig. 5A). In addition, nearly\nhalf of the  alpha-actinin-2-expressing cells were colabeled for low\nlevels of nNOS [neuronal nitric oxide synthase] (44.0 +/- 2.7%, n = 50) or NPY (52.1 +/- 1.8%, n =\n48), and virtually none coexpressed the Ca2 -binding protein\nCR [calretinin] (Fig. 5A)."', 'p 1600 left bot', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2453, 160902, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"The tyramide\nsignal amplification method was used to study the colocalization of\nCOUP-TFII, cholecystokinin (CCK), parvalbumin (PV) and SM, making\nit possible to detect two molecules with primary antibodies raised in\nthe same species. Briefly, SM was detected with a very low concentration\nof mouse monoclonal primary antibody (diluted 1:50,000 1:100,000)\nincubated overnight and then incubated with a biotinylated-secondary\nantibody (1:100) overnight, followed by avidin-biotinylated-horseradish\nperoxidase complex for 1 d (ABC elite kit, Vector Laboratories). Next, a\nhorseradish peroxidase enzyme reaction was performed with biotinylated tyramide (TSA INDIRECT, PerkinElmer Life Sciences, 1:1000 1:3000)\nfor 1 h; which was then revealed with streptavidin conjugated to a fluorophore\n(see next paragraph) incubated overnight. Next, the standard\ninmmunoreaction protocol was followed to detect the other molecules\n(COUP-TFII, monoclonal mouse antibody; CCK, rabbit antibody and\nPV, guinea pig antibody) in the same tissue."', 'p 1596 left bot', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2454, 160902, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2455, 160903, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Table 1. Molecular expression profiles of COUP-TFII-expressing interneuron types\nrecorded in vivo"', 'p 1603 ', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2456, 160903, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"The tyramide\nsignal amplification method was used to study the colocalization of\nCOUP-TFII, cholecystokinin (CCK), parvalbumin (PV) and SM, making\nit possible to detect two molecules with primary antibodies raised in\nthe same species. Briefly, SM was detected with a very low concentration\nof mouse monoclonal primary antibody (diluted 1:50,000 1:100,000)\nincubated overnight and then incubated with a biotinylated-secondary\nantibody (1:100) overnight, followed by avidin-biotinylated-horseradish\nperoxidase complex for 1 d (ABC elite kit, Vector Laboratories). Next, a\nhorseradish peroxidase enzyme reaction was performed with biotinylated tyramide (TSA INDIRECT, PerkinElmer Life Sciences, 1:1000 1:3000)\nfor 1 h; which was then revealed with streptavidin conjugated to a fluorophore\n(see next paragraph) incubated overnight. Next, the standard\ninmmunoreaction protocol was followed to detect the other molecules\n(COUP-TFII, monoclonal mouse antibody; CCK, rabbit antibody and\nPV, guinea pig antibody) in the same tissue."', 'p 1596 left bot', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2457, 160903, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2458, 160904, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"We have previously\nreported on the light microscopic and ultrastructural\ndetails of entorhinal parvalbumin-containing neurons\nand their connectivity with principal neurons\n(Wouterlood et al., 1995). These parvalbumin neurons appear\nto be one of the subsets of the GABA[gamma aminobutyric acid]ergic interneurons\n(Miettienen et al., 1996). Among these neurons, the\nbasket neurons in layer II strongly inhibit the principal\nentorhinal cells projecting to the dentate gyrus (Buhl and\nJones, 1993)."', 'p 178 left top', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2459, 160904, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', NULL, NULL, 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2460, 160904, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2461, 160906, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Type 1 [calretinin-positive cells in the entorhinal cortex]: bipolar neurons. Bipolar neurons had a\nspindle-like perikaryon smoothly continuing into one ascending\nand, from the opposite pole, descending primary\ndendrite (mean length of the perikaryon 13 microm; mean\nwidth 7 microm; ratio between short and long diameters 1.8\n2.5). The primary dendrites were thin and smooth, and\nbifurcated into thinner distal dendrites at some distance\nfrom their parent cell body (Figs. 3A,B, 4A). Bipolar cells\nwere present both in LEA [lateral entorhinal area] and MEA [medial entorhinal area]; they occurred in\nlayers II and III and deeper (Fig. 4A)."', 'p 181 right bot', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2462, 160906, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Sections were rinsed in 50 mM Tris-buffered saline, pH\n8.0, with 0.5% Triton X-100 (TBS-TX; Triton X-100 from\nJanssen Chimica, Geel, Belgium) and incubated for 48\nhours in various concentrations of anti-calretinin antibodies\nraised in rabbit (Sigma, St. Louis, MO; usually diluted\n1:2500 in TBS-TX)."', 'p 178 right top', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2463, 160906, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2464, 160908, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Type 2 [calretinin-positive cells in the entorhinal cortex]: multipolar neurons. Multipolar cells displayed\nirregularly shaped perikarya. In most cases, the\ndendrites arose abruptly from these cells (in strong contrast\nto the smooth transition as occurred in bipolar cells).\nThe dendritic trees of multipolar cells extended in all\ndirections. Most multipolar cells, notably those superficial\nto the lamina dissecans, displayed intensely stained\nperikarya."', 'p 181 right bot', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2465, 160908, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Sections were rinsed in 50 mM Tris-buffered saline, pH\n8.0, with 0.5% Triton X-100 (TBS-TX; Triton X-100 from\nJanssen Chimica, Geel, Belgium) and incubated for 48\nhours in various concentrations of anti-calretinin antibodies\nraised in rabbit (Sigma, St. Louis, MO; usually diluted\n1:2500 in TBS-TX)."', 'p 178 right top', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2466, 160908, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2467, 160910, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Subtype A [of multipolar calretinin-positve cells in the entorhinal cortex]: small spherical multipolar neurons. These\ncells had nearly spherical, relatively small, and markedly\nstained cell bodies with diameters ranging between 8 and\n12 microm (Fig. 4B). From the perikarya typically three to four\nshort, curved, and smooth dendrites emanated that\nbranched after a short distance, forming thin, short, and\nsmooth secondary dendrites. The dendritic trees of such\ncells (maximum diameter approximately 100 microm) were\ngenerally restricted to the parent cortical layer. Small\nmultipolar cells were the only calretinin cell type in layer\nI, with a remarkably constant morphology. In LEA [lateral entorhinal cortex], small\nmultipolar cells were frequently located just below the\ndense fiber layer Ia, with dendrites penetrating layer Ia.\nIn MEA [medial entorhinal cortex], where layer Ia was not present, small spherical\nmultipolars occurred scattered in layer I, with dendrites\nreaching the pial surface.\nSmall spherical multipolar cells occurred not only in\nlayer I but also in layers III and VVI of both LEA and\nMEA. We were unable to follow the axons emerging from\nthese neurons."', 'p 182 right top', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2468, 160910, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Sections were rinsed in 50 mM Tris-buffered saline, pH\n8.0, with 0.5% Triton X-100 (TBS-TX; Triton X-100 from\nJanssen Chimica, Geel, Belgium) and incubated for 48\nhours in various concentrations of anti-calretinin antibodies\nraised in rabbit (Sigma, St. Louis, MO; usually diluted\n1:2500 in TBS-TX)."', 'p 178 right top', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2469, 160910, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2470, 160912, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Subtype B [of multipolar calretinin-positve cells in the entorhinal cortex]: large multipolar cells. Neurons of this subclass\nhad a relatively large cell body and large dendritic\ntrees (Figs. 3BD, 4C, cell C)."', 'p 182 right mid', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2471, 160912, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Sections were rinsed in 50 mM Tris-buffered saline, pH\n8.0, with 0.5% Triton X-100 (TBS-TX; Triton X-100 from\nJanssen Chimica, Geel, Belgium) and incubated for 48\nhours in various concentrations of anti-calretinin antibodies\nraised in rabbit (Sigma, St. Louis, MO; usually diluted\n1:2500 in TBS-TX)."', 'p 178 right top', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2472, 160912, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2473, 160914, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Perikaryal diameters\nranged between 15 and 18 microm. The thickest dendrites extended\nfrom the somata at various angles toward the pial\nsurface, whereas thinner dendrites radiated laterally and\ntoward the deep layers."', 'p 182 right mid', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2474, 160914, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Sections were rinsed in 50 mM Tris-buffered saline, pH\n8.0, with 0.5% Triton X-100 (TBS-TX; Triton X-100 from\nJanssen Chimica, Geel, Belgium) and incubated for 48\nhours in various concentrations of anti-calretinin antibodies\nraised in rabbit (Sigma, St. Louis, MO; usually diluted\n1:2500 in TBS-TX)."', 'p 178 right top', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2475, 160914, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2476, 160916, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Cells of this\nsubtype [entorhinal cortex large multipolar cells] displayed the longest dendrites; for instance, cell\nbodies could lie in layer III, with dendrites traversing\nlayer II to into layer I and ending near the pial surface."', 'p 182 right mid', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2477, 160916, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Sections were rinsed in 50 mM Tris-buffered saline, pH\n8.0, with 0.5% Triton X-100 (TBS-TX; Triton X-100 from\nJanssen Chimica, Geel, Belgium) and incubated for 48\nhours in various concentrations of anti-calretinin antibodies\nraised in rabbit (Sigma, St. Louis, MO; usually diluted\n1:2500 in TBS-TX)."', 'p 178 right top', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2478, 160916, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2479, 160918, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Subtype C [of multipolar calretinin-positve cells in the entorhinal cortex]: multipolar cells with laterally extending dendritic\ntrees. Some multipolar neurons displayed main\ndendrites oriented roughly parallel to the brain surface.\nMost cells belonging to this subtype were located deep in\nlayer I or in the upper part of layer III, and they extended\nsecondary dendrites into layer II. Most cells of this subtype\nwere in the ventrolateral portion of LEA [lateral entorhinal area]."', 'p 182 right bot', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2480, 160918, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Sections were rinsed in 50 mM Tris-buffered saline, pH\n8.0, with 0.5% Triton X-100 (TBS-TX; Triton X-100 from\nJanssen Chimica, Geel, Belgium) and incubated for 48\nhours in various concentrations of anti-calretinin antibodies\nraised in rabbit (Sigma, St. Louis, MO; usually diluted\n1:2500 in TBS-TX)."', 'p 178 right top', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2481, 160918, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2482, 160920, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Following injection of HRP [horse radish peroxidase] in the hippocampal formation\nof two animals, abundant retrograde labeling was\npresent of principal entorhinal cells in layers II and III.\nThis labeling was visible as a granular, blue-black deposit\nin the cell bodies and in the main dendrites closest to the\ncell bodies. The HRP reaction product could easily be\ndistinguished from the homogeneously distributed brown\ncalretinin immunoreaction product. All retrogradely labeled\nentorhinal cells did not contain calretinin-associated,\nbrown immunoreaction product."', 'p 188 left top', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2483, 160920, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Sections were rinsed in 50 mM Tris-buffered saline, pH\n8.0, with 0.5% Triton X-100 (TBS-TX; Triton X-100 from\nJanssen Chimica, Geel, Belgium) and incubated for 48\nhours in various concentrations of anti-calretinin antibodies\nraised in rabbit (Sigma, St. Louis, MO; usually diluted\n1:2500 in TBS-TX)."', 'p 178 right top', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2484, 160920, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2485, 160922, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Remarkably, in layer I, where only one type of calretinin\ncell was seen (small spherical multipolar cells), we found\nco-localization with GABA [gamma aminobutyric acid] in 28% of the calretinin-positive\ncells."', 'p 188 left mid', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2486, 160922, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Sections were rinsed in 50 mM Tris-buffered saline, pH\n8.0, with 0.5% Triton X-100 (TBS-TX; Triton X-100 from\nJanssen Chimica, Geel, Belgium) and incubated for 48\nhours in various concentrations of anti-calretinin antibodies\nraised in rabbit (Sigma, St. Louis, MO; usually diluted\n1:2500 in TBS-TX)."', 'p 178 right top', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2487, 160922, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2488, 160924, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"These sections showed\nan abundance of cells expressing only one of the markers [parvalbumin and calretinin].\nCells in which the two immunofluorescent labels coexisted\nwere conspicuously absent. These results indicate\nthat there is a complete segregation of populations of\nentorhinal parvalbumin- and calretinin-immunoreactive\ncells."', 'p 188 left bot', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2489, 160924, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Sections were rinsed in 50 mM Tris-buffered saline, pH\n8.0, with 0.5% Triton X-100 (TBS-TX; Triton X-100 from\nJanssen Chimica, Geel, Belgium) and incubated for 48\nhours in various concentrations of anti-calretinin antibodies\nraised in rabbit (Sigma, St. Louis, MO; usually diluted\n1:2500 in TBS-TX)."', 'p 178 right top', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2490, 160924, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2491, 160926, '2012-10-14 16:08:24', '"Our findings concerning\nco-localization of calretinin and GABA [gamma aminobutyric acid] are in conflict\nwith the observation by Miettienen et al. (1997), who\nreported that nearly 100% of the calretinin-positive cells\nin the superficial layers of the entorhinal cortex co-express\nglutamic acid decarboxylase (GAD; rate-limiting metabolic\nenzyme of GABA) or GABA. The methodology used\nby Miettienen et al. should therefore be compared with the\ndouble-fluorescence CLSM [confocal laser scanning microscopy] method used by us.\nMiettienen et al. (1997) employed Kosaka et al.s (1985)\nmirror method, which is based on the principle that some\ncells in tissue being sectioned will be spliced into parts,\nwith these parts present (and their position identifiable)\nin adjacent sections. After treating adjacent sections with\nprimary antibodies against different markers, it can be\ndetermined whether co-localization exits by inspecting the\nfragments of the spliced cells in the adjacent sections.\nAccurate counting of double-immunoreactive neurons can\nonly be done with the mirror method when all cell bodies\nare likely to be sectioned, which occurs when the section\nthickness is the same or less than the diameter of the cells\nunder study. This imposes a constraint on this method\n(false negativity by undersampling).\nOptical sectioning by means of a confocal instrument,\ntogether with the image acquisition procedure, ensured\nthat all calretinin- and GABA-immunopositive cells in\neach section were recorded in their cytoarchitectonic context\nand that no neuron was counted twice, whatever the\nlocation, superficially or deep in a section. By means of\nhigh-magnification two-channel confocal analysis, we\nscreened every single calretinin-positive cell for colocalization\nwith GABA, and we are confident that the low\nnumber of double-labeled cells is not caused by missing a\nparticular neuron population due to undersampling. Finally,\nthe excitation-emission characteristics of the fluorophores\nwe used [Cy2 (green) and Cy5 (infrared)] do not\noverlap (Wouterlood et al., 1998). For this reason we can\nrule out false positivity caused by the notorious bleeding\nthrough of one label in the channel designed to visualize\nthe second label.\nWe felt, however, less confident about false negativity.\nFalse-negative results may occur when in a cocktail of\nprimary antisera the penetration of one antibody is less\nthan that of the other. To check this, we incubated control\nsections with the specific purpose of monitoring penetration\ndeficits of the antisera and possible competition or\nexclusion artifacts. In the sections stained with antibodies\nagainst parvalbumin and GABA, there was 100% colocalization,\nwhile all parvalbumin-positive neurons were\nstained completely."', 'p 190 left mid', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2492, 160926, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"Sections were rinsed in 50 mM Tris-buffered saline, pH\n8.0, with 0.5% Triton X-100 (TBS-TX; Triton X-100 from\nJanssen Chimica, Geel, Belgium) and incubated for 48\nhours in various concentrations of anti-calretinin antibodies\nraised in rabbit (Sigma, St. Louis, MO; usually diluted\n1:2500 in TBS-TX)."', 'p 178 right top', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2493, 160926, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2494, 160928, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"Two cell types could be distinguished: bipolar and multipolar\nneurons (cf. Miettienen et al., 1997). The multipolar\ncells were the most common and could be further\nsubdivided. One of the subtypes, the small spherical cell,\ndisplayed dendrites, which were confined within the parent\ncortical layer. All calretinin-positive cells in layer I\nbelong to this subtype. In all other cortical layers, several\nadditional calretinin-positive cell types occurred, such as\nbipolar cells, large multipolar cells, and multipolar cells\nwith laterally extending dendrites."', 'p 190 right bot', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2495, 160928, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"Sections were rinsed in 50 mM Tris-buffered saline, pH\n8.0, with 0.5% Triton X-100 (TBS-TX; Triton X-100 from\nJanssen Chimica, Geel, Belgium) and incubated for 48\nhours in various concentrations of anti-calretinin antibodies\nraised in rabbit (Sigma, St. Louis, MO; usually diluted\n1:2500 in TBS-TX)."', 'p 178 right top', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2496, 160928, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2497, 160930, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"Only a fraction (28\n29%) of the calretinin-immunofluorescent neurons in layer\nI [small spherical multipolar cells] expressed also GABA immunofluorescence. This finding\nimplies that this layer contains (at least) two classes of\nneuron that appear morphologically similar but are chemically\ninhomogeneous."', 'p 190 right bot', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2498, 160930, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"Sections were rinsed in 50 mM Tris-buffered saline, pH\n8.0, with 0.5% Triton X-100 (TBS-TX; Triton X-100 from\nJanssen Chimica, Geel, Belgium) and incubated for 48\nhours in various concentrations of anti-calretinin antibodies\nraised in rabbit (Sigma, St. Louis, MO; usually diluted\n1:2500 in TBS-TX)."', 'p 178 right top', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2499, 160930, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2500, 160932, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"An important observation in the present study is that\nmost calretinin-positive axon terminals in the entorhinal\ncortex form asymmetrical synapses with their postsynaptic\ntargets."', 'p 191 right mid', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2501, 160932, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', NULL, NULL, 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2502, 160932, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2503, 160934, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"Both in CA1 and CA3 another dense VIP[vasoactive intestinal polypeptide]-positive\naxon terminal plexus was present in stratum pyramidale.\nThe varicosities surrounded the immunonegative\nsomata of pyramidal cells and proximal dendrites\nin a basket-like manner (Fig. 1C), but occasionally\nlarger non-pyramidal-like cell bodies in the same\nlayer were also innervated."', 'p 301 right top', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2504, 160934, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"[1] For single immunostaining rabbit anti-calretinin\n(1:5000), 36 or rabbit anti-VIP (1: 10,000) (13) or rabbit anti-\nCCK (1:3000) (13) or monoclonal mouse anti-GABA (1:50) (45)\nwere used as primary antisera.  [2] For fluorescent double-staining the following mixtures\nof antisera were used: rabbit anti-VIP (1 : 5000) and mouse\nanti-calbindin (1:2000) (10) or rabbit anti-VIP and mouse\nanti-parvalbumin (1:500) (10) or rabbit anti-VIP and\nmouse anti-GABA (1:30). (45)"', 'p 300 left bot, right mid', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2505, 160934, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2506, 160936, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"VIP[vasoactive intestinal polypeptide]-positive\naxons in [CA1 and CA3] stratum radiatum were seen to form\nbaskets around unstained cell bodies, and appeared\nto follow their proximal dendrites."', 'p 301 right top', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2507, 160936, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"[1] For single immunostaining rabbit anti-calretinin\n(1:5000), 36 or rabbit anti-VIP (1: 10,000) (13) or rabbit anti-\nCCK (1:3000) (13) or monoclonal mouse anti-GABA (1:50) (45)\nwere used as primary antisera.  [2] For fluorescent double-staining the following mixtures\nof antisera were used: rabbit anti-VIP (1 : 5000) and mouse\nanti-calbindin (1:2000) (10) or rabbit anti-VIP and mouse\nanti-parvalbumin (1:500) (10) or rabbit anti-VIP and\nmouse anti-GABA (1:30). (45)"', 'p 300 left bot, right mid', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2508, 160936, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2509, 160938, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"VIP-positive cells with an\naxon projecting straight to the O/A border were\nfound in the stratum pyramidale and in the proximal\nstratum radiatum of the CA1 region (Fig. 2). The\nsomata were round or fusiform bearing two to four\nprimary dendrites which branched distally from the\ncell body forming a tuft in stratum lacunosum-moleculare\nand sometimes in stratum oriens."', 'p 301 right bot', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2510, 160938, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"[1] For single immunostaining rabbit anti-calretinin\n(1:5000), 36 or rabbit anti-VIP (1: 10,000) (13) or rabbit anti-\nCCK (1:3000) (13) or monoclonal mouse anti-GABA (1:50) (45)\nwere used as primary antisera.  [2] For fluorescent double-staining the following mixtures\nof antisera were used: rabbit anti-VIP (1 : 5000) and mouse\nanti-calbindin (1:2000) (10) or rabbit anti-VIP and mouse\nanti-parvalbumin (1:500) (10) or rabbit anti-VIP and\nmouse anti-GABA (1:30). (45)"', 'p 300 left bot, right mid', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2511, 160938, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2512, 160940, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"In CA1, two\nsubtypes [of vasoactive intestinal peptide-positive neurons] were distinguished on the basis of dendritic\narbour. The most characteristic feature of the first\nsubtype is the dendritic arbour restricted to stratum\nlacunosum-moleculare, thus, it is likely to receive\ninput mostly if not exclusively from the entorhinal\ncortex (cells 2, 3, 6 in Fig. 3). The round and small\n(10-12 microm) cell bodies are located at the border of\nstratum radiatum and stratum lacunosum-moleculare,\nhave few primary dendrites, which branch close\nto the soma and fan out into stratum lacunosummoleculare,\nwhere they arborize profusely. Axon\ninitial segments are oriented towards stratum radiatum.\nThe main axons have a straight course through\nstratum radiatum bearing several collaterals, which\nare mainly vertical, and are studded with numerous\nterminals. In some cases the axons could be followed\nto stratum pyramidale and oriens, but the overwhelming\nmajority of varicosities were always in\nstratum radiatum."', 'p 303 left mid', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2513, 160940, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"[1] For single immunostaining rabbit anti-calretinin\n(1:5000), 36 or rabbit anti-VIP (1: 10,000) (13) or rabbit anti-\nCCK (1:3000) (13) or monoclonal mouse anti-GABA (1:50) (45)\nwere used as primary antisera.  [2] For fluorescent double-staining the following mixtures\nof antisera were used: rabbit anti-VIP (1 : 5000) and mouse\nanti-calbindin (1:2000) (10) or rabbit anti-VIP and mouse\nanti-parvalbumin (1:500) (10) or rabbit anti-VIP and\nmouse anti-GABA (1:30). (45)"', 'p 300 left bot, right mid', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2514, 160940, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2515, 160942, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"Dendrites of the other subtype [of  CA1 vasoactive intestinal peptide-positive neurons] spanned all layers\n(cells 1, 5 in Fig. 3). Their cell bodies were round or\novoid, bipolar or oligopolar, and were located in\nstratum pyramidale or stratum radiatum. The axons\nwere similar to the other subtype, the mostly vertically\noriented collaterals arborized in stratum radiatum\nor rarely in stratum pyramidale or stratum\noriens."', 'p 303 left bot', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2516, 160942, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"[1] For single immunostaining rabbit anti-calretinin\n(1:5000), 36 or rabbit anti-VIP (1: 10,000) (13) or rabbit anti-\nCCK (1:3000) (13) or monoclonal mouse anti-GABA (1:50) (45)\nwere used as primary antisera.  [2] For fluorescent double-staining the following mixtures\nof antisera were used: rabbit anti-VIP (1 : 5000) and mouse\nanti-calbindin (1:2000) (10) or rabbit anti-VIP and mouse\nanti-parvalbumin (1:500) (10) or rabbit anti-VIP and\nmouse anti-GABA (1:30). (45)"', 'p 300 left bot, right mid', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2517, 160942, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2518, 160944, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"In the CA3 region only the second subtype was\ndetected with similar morphological characteristics.\nIn addition to stratum radiatum some of them innervated\nstratum oriens as well (Fig. 4)."', 'p 303 right top', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2519, 160944, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"[1] For single immunostaining rabbit anti-calretinin\n(1:5000), 36 or rabbit anti-VIP (1: 10,000) (13) or rabbit anti-\nCCK (1:3000) (13) or monoclonal mouse anti-GABA (1:50) (45)\nwere used as primary antisera.  [2] For fluorescent double-staining the following mixtures\nof antisera were used: rabbit anti-VIP (1 : 5000) and mouse\nanti-calbindin (1:2000) (10) or rabbit anti-VIP and mouse\nanti-parvalbumin (1:500) (10) or rabbit anti-VIP and\nmouse anti-GABA (1:30). (45)"', 'p 300 left bot, right mid', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2520, 160944, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2521, 160946, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"The axon [of vasoactive intestinal polypeptide-positive neurons with cell bodies in or close to stratum pyramidale in CA1 and CA3] was oriented mostly towards stratum\npyramidale, and in most cases sharply terminated\nwithout fading immediately beyond the initial segment,\nsuggesting that it became myelinated. In several\nsections with darker osmium treatment the\noutline of the myelin sheath was clearly visible, and\ncould even be followed for some distance. Occasionally,\nthin collaterals originating from a proximal\nunmyelinated segment were seen to surround the\nsomata of pyramidal cells, but were soon lost in the\ndense perisomatic plexus formed by the varicose\naxons of this VIP-positive cell type. On the basis of\nthese morphological characteristics we defined the\nneurons of this type as basket cells."', 'p 303 right top', 'data', NULL, NULL),
(2522, 160946, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"[1] For single immunostaining rabbit anti-calretinin\n(1:5000), 36 or rabbit anti-VIP (1: 10,000) (13) or rabbit anti-\nCCK (1:3000) (13) or monoclonal mouse anti-GABA (1:50) (45)\nwere used as primary antisera.  [2] For fluorescent double-staining the following mixtures\nof antisera were used: rabbit anti-VIP (1 : 5000) and mouse\nanti-calbindin (1:2000) (10) or rabbit anti-VIP and mouse\nanti-parvalbumin (1:500) (10) or rabbit anti-VIP and\nmouse anti-GABA (1:30). (45)"', 'p 300 left bot, right mid', 'protocol', NULL, NULL),
(2523, 160946, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', NULL, NULL, 'animal', NULL, NULL),
(2524, 160948, '2012-10-14 16:08:25', '"We examined\na total of 65 cells and 50% (26 out of 52) of the\nVIP-immunoreactive cells in CA1 and 54% (seven\nout of 13) in the CA3 were shown to be positive for\ncalretinin. Interneurons co-localizing calretinin and\nVIP represented 37% of calretinin-containing cells in\nthe CAl and 11% in the CA3 subfield. In CA3, none\nof the double-labelled cells belonged to the spiny type\nof calretinin-positive neurons. (14)"', 'p 308 left', 'data', NULL, NULL),
