(1000, 101, '2012-10-14 16:07:27', 'DG (+)2201p-CA3 00110 granule cells (GC)', 'Granule (+)2201p', 'active', 'Status: Active.\r\n\r\nMerger status: No current merger proposals.\r\n\r\nCross-references: None.\r\n\r\nNotes: Desmond (1982) and Hosseini-Sharifabad (2007) have been added to the end of the packet.\r\n\r\nOn page 20, Claiborne (1986), in the Figure 16 caption, clearly states that contact is made with both the apical and basal dendrites of CA3 pyramidal neurons, which substantiates the A:CA3:SP interpretation.\r\n \r\nSmall collaterals can extend into SG and SMi.  A:SG are more dorsal than ventral and only contact through en passant boutons.\r\n\r\nBuckmaster (1999) and Blasco-Ibбсez (2000): evidence for some A:SMi, in particular at the temporal pole of the hippocampus.\r\n\r\nClaiborne (1986): axons pass through CA3c SR.\r\n\r\nBlaabjerg (2007): the most temporal levels in rat have A:CA1; European hedgehogs have A:CA1:SL; BALB/cJ mice have only an intrapyramidal bundle; SM/J mice have only an infrapyramidal bundle; septally there are almost equal infrapyramidal and suprapyramidal projections with minor intrapyramidal projections; transitioning more temporally the infra- and intrapyramidal projections go away; and infrapyramidal is interpreted as an extended part of SP.\r\n\r\nAxons form asymmetric synapses.  Mossy boutons contact DG mossy cells and CA3 pyramidal neurons.  Fine filopodial processes contact GABAergic and peptidergic interneurons in DG:H and CA3.  A:DG:SG contact dendrites and somata of non-GCs, and A:DG:H & A:CA3 contact somata, dendrites, and spines of GABAergic interneurons.\r\n\r\nClaiborne (1990): 63% of dendritic branch points and 30% of the length in SMi_SG.  37% of branch points and 70% of the length in SMo.\r\n\r\nDesmond (1982): most 1st-order DТs in SG and lengths depend on depth of somata in SG; mostly 2nd-, 3rd-, 4th-order dendrites in SMi; mostly 3rd-, 4th-, 5th-order dendrites in SMo; most dendritic branching occurs in SG and SMi; and most dendritic segments located in and terminate in distal SM.\r\n\r\nDendrites are spiny.  \r\n\r\nD:SG within 100 microm of the soma are considered to be part of the soma.\r\n\r\nIn Geiger (1997) and Lьbke (1998) the youngest rats may be adolescents.\r\n\r\nHosseini-Sharifabad and Nyengaard (2007): 0.24-2.17 million GC''s depending on species.'),
(1001, 102, '2012-10-14 16:07:27', 'DG (+)2311p-CA3 00100 semilunar granule cells (SGC)', 'Semilunar granule (+)2311p', 'active', 'Status:\r\nActive.\r\n\r\nMerger status:\r\nNo current merger proposals.\r\n\r\nCross-references:\r\nDG (+)2201p granule cells (GC) (active)\r\n\r\nNotes:\r\nLarimer and Strowbridge (2010) has been added. - CLR\r\n\r\nAll SGC neurons have D:SMo_SMi and A:H.\r\n\r\nIn Williams (2007), 4 of 10 reconstructions have A:SM, which is later restated as not all reconstructions have A:SMi.  3 of these 4 reconstructions have A:SG.\r\n\r\nUnable to infer about the presence of A:SG when there is no A:SMi, so insufficient data to establish a second (suspended) class.\r\n\r\nSGCs and GCs share polarized dendrites, similar sized somata, and a primary axon directed toward H.\r\n\r\nContact mossy cells and interneurons in the hilus.\r\n\r\nIn Larimer (2010), perforant path stimulation is interpreted as D:SMo.\r\n\r\nIn Larimer (2010), the youngest rats may be adolescents.\r\n\r\n'),
(1002, 105, '2012-10-14 16:07:27', 'DG (+)0103 mossy cells (MC)', 'Mossy (+)0103', 'active', 'Status: Active.\r\n\r\nMerger status: No current merger proposals.\r\n\r\nCross-references: DG (+)2323 mossy cells (suspended)\r\n\r\nNotes:\r\nAll A:SG interpretations have been changed into comments instead.\r\n\r\nAxonal lengths (avg. of 3 cells): SMo = 4%, SMi = 57%, SG = 7%, H = 26%, CA3 = 3%, CA1 = 1%.\r\n\r\nAxonal synapses: H = 15%, SG = 3%, SMi = 82%.\r\n\r\nNo A:SG contacts in deep SG and only sparse A:SG contacts onto dendritic spines and shafts and a GC soma.\r\n\r\nAmaral (1978) states D:SM in young (<14 d) and old (18 m) but not at 28 d.\r\n\r\nRibak et al. (1985) states occasional D:SM_SG but rarely in mature brain.\r\n\r\nDendrites appear to avoid CA3.\r\n\r\nThorny excrescences on proximal dendrites and somata and spines on distal dendrites.\r\n\r\nExcitatory asymmetric synapses.\r\n\r\nA:H primarily contact GABA-positive dendritic shafts, some somata, and GABA-negative dendritic spines. \r\n\r\nA:SG contact dendritic spines and shafts and GC somata.\r\n\r\nA:SMi primarily contact GC proximal dendritic spines.\r\n\r\nIn Lübke et al. (1998) some of the youngest rats may be adolescents.\r\n\r\nThe spiny hilar cells of Scharfman (1990) were considered for this packet and rejected due to D:SMo_SMi and no axonal information.\r\n\r\nThe mossy cells of Soltesz et al. (1993) were considered for this packet and determined to be DG (+)2323 mossy cells in another packet.\r\n\r\nPacket rating:'),
(1004, 106, '2012-10-14 16:07:27', 'DG (-)3303 total molecular layer (TML) cells', 'Total molecular (-)3303', 'active', 'Status:\r\nActive.\r\n\r\nMerger status:\r\nNo current merger proposals.\r\n\r\nCross-references:\r\nDG (-)3302 TML-MOLAX neurons (active)\r\nDG (-)1220 OML neurons (need approval for suspension)\r\n\r\nNotes: Mott Figure 5 (p. 4) has been added for reference.\r\n\r\nMott 1997 dendrite interpretation has been added and the soma interpretation has been removed.\r\n\r\nBartos (2010): A:SG is less than 15%.'),
